(background: I am a software engineering Master's student at the University of Waterloo under the (co-)supervision of Vijay Ganesh. In collaboration with Yunhui Zheng (IBM Research) we are developing a new version of the Z3str2 string solver. The previous implementation of Z3str2 was built against a now-obsolete version of Z3 and relies on some hacks because it had to be built totally outside the main codebase. This version of the string solver is being developed as a first-class theory plugin within the latest version of Z3.

So far my efforts in porting this code have been successful, although I am far from being done with the initial implementation. I am working on my code in the 'develop' branch at [my fork of Z3](https://github.com/mtrberzi/z3). I plan to create a pull request once the basic solver is ready and has been tested carefully.)

While developing the string theory plugin, I ran into an interesting bug related to asserting theory axioms. I found that implications that are asserted with `get_context().mk_th_axiom()` are totally ignored by the core solver. This is best shown with a short example. I want to assert the implication `(Concat X Y) == "" -> X == ""`. (In other words, if the concatenation of X and Y is equal to the empty string, then X must also be equal to the empty string.) Here's the code that I'm using to generate the axiom:

```
expr_ref premise(ctx.mk_eq_atom(concat, emptystr), m);
expr_ref conclusion(ctx.mk_eq_atom(x, emptystr), m);
expr_ref axiom(m.mk_implies(premise, conclusion), m);
```

Then I assert `axiom` with the following, which I believe is borrowed from theory_fpa:

```
void theory_str::assert_axiom(expr * e) {
    if (get_manager().is_true(e)) return;
    context & ctx = get_context();
    if (!ctx.b_internalized(e)) {
        ctx.internalize(e, true);
    }
    literal lit(ctx.get_literal(e));
    ctx.mark_as_relevant(lit);
    ctx.mk_th_axiom(get_id(), 1, &lit);
}
```

When I later display the entire set of assignments (in `final_check_eh`), I can see the axiom I've asserted among them. However, I also noticed that the solver can enter a state where it believes the truth of A, A->B, and not(B) simultaneously. In this case I can add the assertions `(= (Concat X Y) "")` and `(not (= X ""))` to the initial instance, see that the axiom `(=> (= (Concat X Y) "") (= X ""))` is correctly generated, and then see that the solver simultaneously believes that all three of these facts are true.

I can modify the premise and conclusion to be anything I want and the solver will still accept it regardless of what other facts it believes. I can even assert the implication (=> true false) as an axiom in this fashion and the solver will still return SAT.

The fix I am using right now is to instead use the following representation for my axiom:

`expr_ref axiom(m.mk_or(m.mk_not(premise), conclusion), m);`

which is equisatisfiable with `(=> premise conclusion)`. This gives the expected result.

